{"title_page": "KOLN (TV)", "text_new": "{{short description|CBS affiliate in Lincoln, Nebraska}}\n{{about|the television station|the city known as K\u00f6ln in [[German language|German]]|Cologne}}\n{{redirect-distinguish|KGIN|KGAN}}\n{{Infobox broadcast \n|  call_letters             = KOLN\n|  city                     = \n|  station_logo             = [[Image:Koln.png|200px]]\n----\n[[File:KSNBNBC4.png|200px]]\n|  station_slogan           = \n|  station_branding         = 10/11 ''(general)''<br>''10/11 Now'' ''(newscasts)''<br>''(pronounced as \"ten-eleven\")''\n|  digital                  = 10 ([[very high frequency|VHF]])\n|  virtual                  = 10 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n|  affiliations             = '''10.1:''' [[CBS]]<br>'''[[KSNB-TV|10.2]]:''' [[NBC]]<br>'''10.3:''' [[MyNetworkTV]]/[[MeTV]]<br>'''10.4:''' [[Heroes & Icons]]\n|  other_chs                = [[KOLN#KOLN translators|See below]]\n|  network                  =\n|  country                  = United States\n|  founded                  =\n|  airdate                  = {{start date and age|1953|2|18|p=y}}\n|  enddate                  =\n|  location                 = [[Lincoln, Nebraska]]\n|  callsign_meaning         = Lin'''K'''(C)'''OLN''' ''([[sic]])''\n|  former_callsigns         = KOLN-TV (1953\u20131986)\n|  former_channel_numbers   = '''Analog:'''<br>12 (VHF, 1953\u20131954)<br>10 (VHF, 1954\u20132009)<br>'''Digital:'''<br>25 ([[Ultra high frequency|UHF]], until 2009)\n|  owner                    = [[Gray Television]]\n|  licensee                 = Gray Television Licensee, [[Limited liability company|LLC]]\n|  sister_stations          = Lincoln: [[KCWH-LD]], [[KSNB-TV]]<br>Hastings: [[KNHL]]<br>[[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]]: [[WOWT]]<br>[[North Platte, Nebraska|North Platte]]: [[KNOP-TV]], [[KNPL-LD]], [[KIIT-CD]]<br>[[Scottsbluff, Nebraska|Scottsbluff]]: [[KNEP]]\n|  former_affiliations      = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (1953\u20131957, secondary from 1954)<br>[[DuMont Television Network|DuMont]] (secondary, 1953\u20131955)\n|  effective_radiated_power = 28 [[kilowatt|kW]]\n|  HAAT                     = {{convert|453.9|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n|  facility_id              = 7890\n|  coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|40|48|11|N|97|10|52|W|type:landmark_scale:2000}}}}\n|  licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n|  homepage                 = {{URL|https://www.1011now.com/}}\n}}\n{{Infobox broadcast \n|  call_letters             = KGIN<br>''([[broadcast relay station#Semi-satellites|semi-satellite]] of KOLN)''\n|  city                     = Grand Island, Nebraska\n|  station_logo             = \n|  station_slogan           = \n|  station_branding         = see KOLN infobox\n|  digital                  = 11 (VHF)\n|  virtual                  = 11 (PSIP)\n|  affiliations             = '''11.1:''' CBS<br>'''11.2:''' NBC<br>'''11.3:''' MyNetworkTV/MeTV<br>'''11.4:''' Heroes & Icons\n|  other_chs                = [[KOLN#KGIN translators|See below]]\n|  network                  =\n|  country                  = United States\n|  founded                  =\n|  airdate                  = {{start date and age|1961|10|1|p=y}}\n|  enddate                  =\n|  location                 = [[Grand Island, Nebraska|Grand Island]]/[[Hastings, Nebraska|Hastings]]/[[Kearney, Nebraska]]\n|  callsign_meaning         = '''G'''rand '''I'''sland<br>'''N'''ebraska\n|  former_callsigns         = KGIN-TV (1961\u20131986)\n|  former_channel_numbers   = '''Analog:'''<br>11 (VHF, 1961\u20132009)<br>'''Digital:'''<br>32 (UHF, until 2009)\n|  owner                    = Gray Television\n|  licensee                 = Gray Television Licensee, LLC\n|  sister_stations          = see KOLN infobox\n|  former_affiliations      = \n|  effective_radiated_power = 25 kW\n|  HAAT                     = {{convert|314.6|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n|  facility_id              = 7894\n|  coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|40|35|14|N|98|48|10|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=KGIN}}}}\n|  licensing_authority      = FCC\n|  homepage                 = \n}}\n'''KOLN''', [[virtual channel|virtual]] and [[very high frequency|VHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 10, is a [[CBS]]-[[network affiliate|affiliated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Lincoln, Nebraska]], United States. The station is owned by [[Gray Television]]. KOLN's studios are located on North 40th Street in Lincoln, and its transmitter is located southeast of [[Goehner, Nebraska|Goehner]]. \n\n'''KGIN''' (virtual and VHF digital channel 11) in [[Grand Island, Nebraska|Grand Island]] operates as a [[broadcast relay station#Semi-satellites|semi-satellite]] of KOLN, serving the central portion of the [[media market|market]]; this station maintains a [[news bureau]] and sales office on West State Street in Grand Island and transmitter facilities near [[Heartwell, Nebraska]]. Collectively branded as '''\"10/11\"''', the two stations serve one of the largest coverage areas in the United States, stretching across 42 counties in southern and central Nebraska\u2014almost two-thirds of the state's geographical land area\u2014and an additional four counties in [[Kansas]].\n\nKOLN/KGIN operates as part of a [[Duopoly (broadcasting)|duopoly]] with [[Superior, Nebraska|Superior]]-licensed [[NBC]] affiliate [[KSNB-TV]] (channel 4), which was acquired by Gray in 2013 and [[simulcast]]s in [[high-definition television|high definition]] on the second [[digital subchannel]] of KOLN/KGIN. It previously broadcast [[MyNetworkTV]] and [[MeTV]] programming, along with central Nebraska-specific newscasts. Following Gray's acquisition of [[Hastings, Nebraska|Hastings]]' NBC affiliate KHAS-TV, the station was shut down and its programming (along with separately-produced newscasts out of Hastings) was moved to KSNB's primary channel, which became the primary NBC affiliate for this vast market. KSNB moved to KHAS' former studio just outside Hastings on [[U.S. Route 281|US 281]], though [[master control]] and some internal operations are based at KOLN's facilities. Since KSNB's signal is spotty in Lincoln itself, KOLN and KGIN continue to simulcast it on their second subchannel, while MyNetworkTV and MeTV programming moved to KOLN and KGIN's third subchannel. Gray reacquired [[KNHL]] (the former KHAS-TV) from Legacy Broadcasting on March 1, 2019, and made it a KSNB satellite to further resolve its signal issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.fcc.gov/public/attachments/DA-19-72A1.pdf|title=Letter|work=CDBS Public Access|publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]]|date=February 12, 2019|accessdate=June 15, 2019}}</ref>  KOLN/KGIN is also [[sister station|sister]] to Lincoln-licensed low-power station [[KCWH-LD]] (channel 18), a [[The CW|CW]] affiliate (through [[The CW Plus]]) that served as a translator for KSNB prior to 2018.\n\n'''[[KNPL-LD]]''' (channel 10) in [[North Platte, Nebraska|North Platte]] operates as an another semi-satellite of KOLN. KOLN serves as a master hub for Gray's Nebraska television stations, with the exception of NBC affiliate [[WOWT]] (channel 6) in [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]].\n\n==History==\nKOLN-TV signed on for the first time on February 18, 1953, on channel 12 as Nebraska's third television station and the first outside [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]]. It was owned by Cornhusker Radio and Television Corporation along with KOLN radio (1400 AM; now [[KLIN]]). In August 1953, it was purchased by broadcasting pioneer [[John Fetzer]].<ref name=\"fetzer-buy\">{{cite web|url=http://americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1954/1954-02-22-BC.pdf| title=Fetzer Pays $300,000 For KFOR-TV Lincoln |last=|first=|work=Broadcasting-Telecasting|date=February 22, 1954|page=66| accessdate=August 27, 2017}}</ref> In February 1954, Fetzer purchased Lincoln's other TV station, [[KFOR-TV (defunct)|KFOR-TV]], channel 10, which had launched a few months after KOLN.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1011now.com/history |title=10/11 Station History |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603054302/http://www.1011now.com/history |archivedate=June 3, 2013 |accessdate=December 2, 2016 }}</ref> To avoid running afoul of FCC ownership regulations (and to create a commercial broadcast monopoly for himself in the Lincoln market<ref name=\"fetzer-monopoly\">{{cite web|url=https://huskeralum.org/alumni-stories/-/asset_publisher/ERkkhz8DM30I/content/alumni-profile-jack-mcbride| title=50 Years of Service NET | last=McGuire| first=Jana| work=Nebraska Alumni Magazine|date = Fall 2004 | accessdate=March 11, 2013}}</ref>), Fetzer moved KOLN to channel 10 and donated the channel 12 facilities and the KFOR license to the [[University of Nebraska]] for its [[non-commercial educational|educational station]], [[Nebraska Educational Telecommunications|KUON-TV]].<ref name=\"kfor\">{{cite video|url=http://nebraskastudies.org/0900/stories/0901_0104_01.html|title=TV Comes to Lincoln, Nebraska|last=Ganzel|first=Bill|work=NebraskaStudies.org|accessdate=March 11, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070908080817/http://www.nebraskastudies.org/0900/stories/0901_0104_01.html|archive-date=2007-09-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the same time, Fetzer obtained FCC permission to boost KOLN's visual [[effective radiated power]] to the then-maximum 316 [[kilowatt|kW]],<ref name=\"fetzer-buy\" /> to be broadcast from a new {{convert|1,000|ft|m|adj=on}} tower {{convert|20|mi|km}} west of Lincoln. (At sign-on, KOLN was broadcasting at 26.9 kW visual ERP from a {{convert|407|ft|m|adj=on}} tower next to its studio.<ref name=\"tower\">{{cite web|url=http://americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1953-TV/TV-Stations-AL-NE-PR-YB-1953.pdf| title=KOLN-TV |last=|first=|work=1953 Telecasting Yearbook-Marketbook|date=|page=168| accessdate=August 27, 2017}}</ref>)\n\nThe station was originally the [[DuMont Television Network]] affiliate for the Omaha/Lincoln market. It picked up the ABC affiliation from KFOR-TV after Fetzer shut down that station in March 1954. Meanwhile, Fetzer persuaded the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) to merge Lincoln with the Hastings\u2013[[Kearney, Nebraska|Kearney]] market in central Nebraska. Lincoln has long been the cultural center for central Nebraska, and Fetzer felt that Lincoln had more in common with this area than Omaha. He also wanted an affiliation with a stronger network. Although Fetzer had a very good relationship with CBS, there was little prospect of taking the CBS affiliation from Omaha's [[KMTV]].\n\nSoon after the FCC made Lincoln the center of the new Lincoln\u2013Hastings\u2013Kearney market, KOLN became a primary CBS affiliate. Omaha wouldn't have a primary ABC affiliate again until [[KETV]] signed on in 1957. DuMont shut down in 1956, and KOLN dropped the remaining ABC shows from the schedule in 1957. During the late 1950s, the station was also briefly affiliated with the [[NTA Film Network]].<ref name=\"Boxoffice7\">{{Cite journal|title=Require Prime Evening Time for NTA Films |journal=Boxoffice |page=13 |date=November 10, 1956 |url=http://issuu.com/boxoffice/docs/boxoffice_111056-1 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090614204506/http://issuu.com/boxoffice/docs/boxoffice_111056-1 |archivedate=June 14, 2009 }}</ref> Along with its more powerful broadcasting signal, KOLN signed on translator after translator across its vast and mostly rural coverage area over the next few years, cementing a dominance that continues to this day.\n\nKGIN-TV debuted on October 1, 1961, as a satellite of KOLN; since then, the two stations have been known on-air as \"10/11.\" During the 1960s, KOLN/KGIN frequently broadcast games of the [[Detroit Tigers]], which Fetzer had bought in 1956.\n\nFetzer began selling off his stations in the 1980s. KOLN/KGIN was among the last to be sold, going to [[George N. Gillett Jr.|Gillett Communications]] in 1984. Gillett sold the pair to Busse Broadcasting in 1987 to make room for Gillett's acquisition of the [[Storer Broadcasting]] stations. Busse merged with current owner Gray Communications, now Gray Television, in 1998.\n\nFrom KFOR-TV's shutdown in March 1954 until [[KLKN]] signed on in 1996, KOLN was the only commercial station in Lincoln, making it one of the largest cities in the country with only one full-power commercial station. The western half of the market had full network service; it was served by KGIN, ABC affiliate [[KHGI-TV]] and NBC affiliate KHAS-TV. Later, future sister station KSNB-TV broke off from NTV and joined with Grand Island-based [[KTVG-TV]] to become the Fox affiliate for the western half of the market. This resulted in a market that had very little basis in television reality; KOLN/KGIN was the only major-network station shared by the entire market (though KTVG/KSNB added a translator in Lincoln). It was only truly realized when [[direct-broadcast satellite]] gained more penetration at the turn of the century.\n\nDespite being the only station in the market, KOLN had no need to air other networks' programming. Most of the Omaha stations provide at least secondary coverage of Lincoln. Until KMTV and WOWT were dropped at the turn of the millennium, most of them were also available on cable.\n\nFor a time in January 2009, the KOLN/KGIN website included a section about a [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate on its second digital subchannel (then used for MyNetworkTV, which was to have moved to a DT3 subcarrier). However, station officials later said there were no immediate plans to launch such a station, describing the page as part of an experimental project not meant for public consumption.<ref name=\"js-kolnnofox\">{{cite news|url=http://www.journalstar.com/articles/2009/01/21/living/gz/video_games/doc4977a2b0e1898215560118.txt|title=KOLN/KGIN-TV explains mysterious \"Fox 10/11' Web sighting|last=Korbelik|first=Jeff|date=January 21, 2009|work=[[Lincoln Journal Star]]|accessdate=January 23, 2009}}</ref> At that time, Fox programming was seen on KSNB-TV (now a sister station to KOLN/KGIN) and [[KTVG-TV]] (channel 17). Although the station refused to rule out launching a digital Fox station in the future, this was rendered moot when then-CW affiliate KCWL-TV relaunched as Fox affiliate KFXL-TV.\n\nThe \"10/11\" brand is so well established in Nebraska that when Gray brought KSNB back on the air in 2012, it initially did so under the branding \"10/11 Central Nebraska.\" Likewise, when it relaunched its longtime translator in [[North Platte, Nebraska|North Platte]] as locally-focused CBS affiliate [[KNPL-LD]], it used the branding \"10/11 North Platte.\"\n\n===KOLN tower collapse===\nOn January 18, 2020, KOLN's transmitter tower near [[Beaver Crossing, Nebraska|Beaver Crossing]] collapsed due to an [[ice storm]]. No one was injured, and the station was able to restore service via additional towers and cable/satellite delivery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.1011now.com/content/news/KOLN-TV-tower-in-Beaver-Crossing-collapses-due-to-ice-storm-567106121.html|title=10/11 signal restored following tower collapse|website=1011now.com|publisher=[[Gray Television]]|date=January 18, 2020|accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Digital television==\n\n===Digital channels===\nThe stations' digital signals are [[multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=KOLN#station |title=RabbitEars TV Query for KOLN |publisher=Rabbitears.info |date= |accessdate=2018-09-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=KGIN#station |title=RabbitEars TV Query for KGIN |publisher=Rabbitears.info |date= |accessdate=2018-09-04}}</ref>\n|-\n| 10.1<br>11.1 || [[1080i]] || rowspan=5| [[16:9]] || KOLN-DT<br>KGIN-DT || Main programming / [[CBS]]\n|- \n| [[KSNB-TV|10.2 / 11.2]] || [[720p]] || KSNB-DT || Simulcast of KSNB-TV / [[NBC]] \n|-\n| [[KSNB-TV|10.3 / 11.3]] || rowspan=3| [[480i]] || MeMy-DT || Simulcast of KSNB-DT2 / [[MyNetworkTV]] & [[MeTV]]\n|-\n| 10.4 / 11.4 || H & I || [[Heroes & Icons]]\n|-\n| 10.5 / 11.5 || Circle || [[Gray_Television#Circle|Circle]]\n|}\n\n[[File:Koln kgin mytv dt2.png|thumb|left|Former \"My TV\" logo, used until 2013]]\n[[UPN]] was broadcast on a DT2 subchannel of KOLN and KGIN under the banner UPN Nebraska; the service switched to [[MyNetworkTV]] in September 2006 and was locally branded as \"MyTV\" until being renamed \"10-11 Central Nebraska\" after the acquisition of KSNB in 2013. It not only airs syndicated programs, [[MeTV]] programming, and the entire MyNetworkTV schedule, but also 10/11-produced programming like ''Pure Nebraska'', ''Star City Buzz'' and ''Prepzone Weekly''.\n\nKOLN/KGIN also produces nightly newscasts, ''My News at 9'', formerly ''Nebraska Central News'' & ''10/11 Central Nebraska News'', targeting all of the viewing area and featuring weather forecasts for both eastern (Lincoln) and central (Grand Island/Hastings/Kearney) Nebraska, which airs at 9 p.m. on KSNB's digital subcarrier and KOLN/KGIN's digital subcarrier. ''My News at 9'' only airs on weekdays at 9 p.m. It is produced and aired in high definition. In June 2014, the MyNetworkTV and MeTV programming was moved to a second subchannel of KSNB, with KSNB's main channel and the KOLN/KGIN subchannels now airing the programming previously seen on KHAS-TV; this includes NBC programming and KHAS-TV's separate Hastings-based news operation, giving Lincoln its first-ever NBC affiliate.<ref name=koln-ksnbnbc>{{cite news|title=KHAS 5.1 Signal Moving to KSNB 4.1|url=http://www.1011now.com/home/headlines/KHAS-51-Signal-Moving-262902001.html|accessdate=June 12, 2014|work=1011now.com|date=June 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140615013016/http://www.1011now.com/home/headlines/KHAS-51-Signal-Moving-262902001.html|archive-date=June 15, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=ljs-ksnbnbc>{{cite news|last1=Korbelik|first1=Jeff|title=KSNB-TV to become an NBC affiliate|url=http://journalstar.com/entertainment/tv-radio/ksnb-tv-to-become-an-nbc-affiliate/article_c6b256a4-5b9b-5574-a3e9-fef365c2abb0.html|accessdate=June 12, 2014|work=[[Lincoln Journal-Star]]|date=June 12, 2014}}</ref> With the purchase of [[KNOP-TV]], Gray merged KOLN/KGIN, KSNB and KNOP to form the Nebraska News & Weather Networks. All weather forecasts on the stations are now branded as the Nebraska Weather Network and feature the Nebraska Weather Network logo instead of a station logo in their visual graphics. The three stations can also cover each other's newscasts. Weather on weekends for KSNB is broadcast from their Lincoln studios in a second green screen facility since KOLN is also on air at the same time, and the same is done for KNOP during the weekday evening newscasts. Many news stories are shared between the stations. The result is that essentially for the first time, there is news from the majority of the coverage areas in almost every newscast.\n\n===Analog-to-digital conversion===\nKOLN aired its digital programming on channel 25, while KGIN aired digital programming on channel 32. Both stations shut down their analog signals at midnight on February 16, 2009, the day prior to the original date in which full-power television stations in the United States were set to [[Digital television transition in the United States|transition from analog to digital broadcasts]] under federal mandate (which was later rescheduled for June 12, 2009):<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |title=DTV Tentative Channel Designations for the First and the Second Rounds |format=PDF |accessdate=2012-03-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |archivedate=2013-08-29 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kolnkgin.com/home/headlines/39140942.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-02-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206204128/http://www.kolnkgin.com/home/headlines/39140942.html |archive-date=2009-02-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.nebraska.tv/Global/story.asp?S=9859961 ]{{dead link|date=September 2018}}</ref>\n* KOLN shut down its analog signal, over [[Very high frequency|VHF]] channel 10; the station's digital signal relocated from its pre-transition [[UHF]] channel 25 to VHF channel 10.\n* KGIN shut down its analog signal, over VHF channel 11; the station's digital signal relocated from its pre-transition UHF channel 32 to VHF channel 11.\n\n==Programming==\n[[broadcast syndication|Syndicated]] programs that air on KOLN/KGIN include ''[[Jeopardy!]]'', ''[[Wheel of Fortune (American game show)|Wheel of Fortune]]'', ''[[Live with Kelly and Ryan]]'', ''[[Inside Edition]]'' and ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'', among others.\n\n==News operation==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:KOLN open.png|thumb|right|10/11 News at 6 p.m. newscast title card{{deletable image-caption|Monday, 14 November 2016}}]] -->\nHistorically, KOLN/KGIN has garnered some of the highest news ratings in the country. Not only was it the only major-network affiliate shared by the entire market for most of the second half of the 20th century, but it was the only commercial station in Lincoln for 40 years.\n\nWell into the 1980s, when nearly every other local television news broadcast began with the latest news, KOLN began its newscasts with the weather report as a service to its mostly rural audience. A. James Ebel, KOLN's general manager from 1954 to 1985, began this practice not long after he arrived, saying years later, \"The first thing I learned when I arrived here in 1954 is that the weather is the No. 1 story in Nebraska.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://journalism.unl.edu/an/spring98/ebel2.html |title=Interview |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030503154302/http://journalism.unl.edu/an/spring98/ebel2.html |archivedate=May 3, 2003 |accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref> Mel Mains served as KOLN's main news anchor for 34 years, from 1961 to 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ne-ba.org/about_us-hall_of_fame.asp?id=18|title= NE BA Hall of Fame}}</ref> Chief meteorologist Ken Siemek has been at the station since 1981.\n\nKOLN/KGIN is one of the few television stations in the United States with a husband/wife anchor team, Jon Vanderford and Taryn Vanderford, who serve as anchors for the station's 4 p.m. newscast and host ''Pure Nebraska'', a rural lifestyle show airing weekdays at 9 a.m.  On September 15, 2007, KOLN/KGIN became the first and only station in the Lincoln\u2013Hastings\u2013Kearney market to broadcast weekend morning newscasts from 7-8 a.m. (The time was later changed to 6:30&nbsp;a.m.-7:30&nbsp;a.m. to accommodate ''Pure Nebraska'''s weekend show on Sundays at 7:30&nbsp;a.m.)  The weekend morning newscasts were later canceled.\n\nOn June 15, 2009, KOLN/KGIN became the first commercial station in Nebraska to broadcast local news in a widescreen format. Then on August 10, 2009, KOLN/KGIN took it one step further to become the first station in Nebraska to launch local news in high definition.  With the change came new graphics and a new website www.1011now.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1011now.com/home/headlines/52883667.html|title=New Website|access-date=2009-08-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815103854/http://www.1011now.com/home/headlines/52883667.html|archive-date=2009-08-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> On September 13, 2010, KOLN/KGIN debuted the market's first 4 p.m. newscast with ''10/11 First at Four''.\n\n=== Notable former on-air staff===\n* [[Leta Powell Drake]] - morning show host/portrayed Kalamity Kate for KOLN-TV's ''Cartoon Corral''*88\n* [[Tom Burse]] - Meteorologist 1981-82. Later meteorologist or Chief Meteorologist in Cincinnati, Miami and [[WBBM-TV|CBS Chicago]].\n* [[Vinita Nair]] - morning show host (early 2000s; later co-host of [[CBS This Morning|CBS This Morning: Saturday]])\n\n==Translators==\nKOLN/KGIN serves its large coverage area with eight translators. Repeaters in bold are owned by Gray Television; all others are owned by local municipalities or organizations. All owned-and-operated repeaters broadcast a multiplexed digital signal including high-definition programming. The remainder broadcast an analog signal.\n\nThe repeater in [[North Platte, Nebraska|North Platte]], [[KNPL-LD]], was formerly a straight translator of KOLN/KGIN. On September 3, 2013, KNPL was re-launched as a semi-satellite of the station, adding local newscasts specific to the North Platte market.\n\n<ref name=tvnc-knplseparate>{{cite news|title=CBS Adding Gray's KNPL As Affiliate|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/66264/cbs-adding-grays-knpl-as-affiliate|accessdate=March 19, 2013|newspaper=TVNewsCheck|date=March 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===KOLN translators===\n{{hidden begin\n|title = List of translators\n|titlestyle = background:pink; text-align:center;\n}}\n{|\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: center;\"\n! colspan=\"11\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Active translators\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|City !! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Callsign !! style=\"text-align:left;\"|City !! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Callsign !! style=\"text-align:left;\"|City !! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Callsign !!\n|-\n||[[Lincoln, Nebraska|Lincoln]]||style=\"width:150px\"|[[KCWH-LD|'''KCWH-LD3''']]\n||[[Neligh, Nebraska|Neligh]]||style=\"width:150px\"|[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=K33OW-D '''K33OW-D''']\n||[[Newport, Nebraska|Newport]]||style=\"width:150px\"|[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=K25GM-D '''K25GM-D''']\n|[[O'Neill, Nebraska|O'Neill]]||style=\"width:150px\"|[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=K43FX-D '''K43FX-D''']\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: center;\"\n! colspan=\"11\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Defunct translators\n|-\n||[[Ainsworth, Nebraska|Ainsworth]]||style=\"width:150px\"|[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=K11KW K11KW]\n|[[Valentine, Nebraska|Valentine]]||style=\"width:150px\"|[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=K69AL K69AL]\n|}\n{{hidden end}}\n\n===KGIN translators===\n{{hidden begin\n|title = List of translators\n|titlestyle = background:pink; text-align:center;\n}}\n{|\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|City !! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Callsign !! style=\"text-align:left;\"|City !! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Callsign !! style=\"text-align:left;\"|City !! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Callsign\n|-\n||[[Cambridge, Nebraska|Cambridge]]||style=\"width:130px\"|[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=K30FV-D '''K30FV-D''']\n||[[Cozad, Nebraska|Cozad]]||style=\"width:130px\"|[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=K24HG-D '''K24HG-D''']\n|[[Gothenburg, Nebraska|Gothenburg]]||style=\"width:130px\"|[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=K28GC-D '''K28GC-D''']\n|-\n|[[Wallace, Nebraska|Wallace]]||style=\"width:130px\"|[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=K33FF-D '''K33FF-D''']\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: center;\"\n! colspan=\"11\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Defunct translators\n|-\n||[[Broken Bow, Nebraska|Broken Bow]]||style=\"width:130px\"|[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=K04CV K04CV]\n||[[North Platte, Nebraska|North Platte]]||style=\"width:130px\"|[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=K04ED K04ED]\n||[[Ord, Nebraska|Ord]]||style=\"width:130px\"|[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=K04HL K04HL]\n|}\n{{hidden end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|https://www.1011now.com/}}\n*{{official website|https://www.ksnblocal4.com/|KOLN-DT2/KGIN-DT2/KSNB-TV website}}\n*{{official website|http://www.1011np.com/|KNPL-LD website}}\n*{{TVQ|KOLN}}\n*{{TVQ|KGIN}}\n*{{TVQ|KNPL}}\n*{{BIA|KOLN|TV|TV}}\n*{{BIA|KGIN|TV|TV}}\n*{{BIA|KNPL|TV|LD}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20030503154059/http://journalism.unl.edu/an/spring98/ebel.html Obituary of A. James Ebel] (longtime KOLN general manager)\n*[http://www.ne-ba.org/about_us-hall_of_fame.asp?id=18 Nebraska Broadcasters Association profile of Mel Mains] (longtime KOLN news anchor)\n*[http://www.journalstar.com/articles/2007/12/24/living/gz/video_games/doc476ef6f457ac0060211329.txt ''Lincoln Journal-Star's'' Jeff Korbelik reports on departure of Randy Lube] (longtime 10/11 news director)\n\n{{Lincoln TV}}\n{{North Platte TV}}\n{{CBS Nebraska}}\n{{NBC Nebraska}}\n{{Gray TV}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koln}}\n[[Category:Television stations in the Lincoln\u2013Hastings\u2013Kearney market|OLN]]\n[[Category:CBS network affiliates]]\n[[Category:NBC subchannel-only network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Heroes & Icons affiliates]]\n[[Category:Gray Television]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1953]]\n[[Category:1953 establishments in Nebraska]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|CBS affiliate in Lincoln, Nebraska}}\n{{about|the television station|the city known as K\u00f6ln in [[German language|German]]|Cologne}}\n{{redirect-distinguish|KGIN|KGAN}}\n{{Infobox broadcast \n|  call_letters             = KOLN\n|  city                     = \n|  station_logo             = [[Image:Koln.png|200px]]\n----\n[[File:KSNBNBC4.png|200px]]\n|  station_slogan           = \n|  station_branding         = 10/11 ''(general)''<br>''10/11 Now'' ''(newscasts)''<br>''(pronounced as \"ten-eleven\")''\n|  digital                  = 10 ([[very high frequency|VHF]])\n|  virtual                  = 10 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n|  affiliations             = '''10.1:''' [[CBS]]<br>'''[[KSNB-TV|10.2]]:''' [[NBC]]<br>'''10.3:''' [[MyNetworkTV]]/[[MeTV]]<br>'''10.4:''' [[Heroes & Icons]]\n|  other_chs                = [[KOLN#KOLN translat